<div class="container py-5">
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-lg-8">
      <h1 class="mb-4">Vaccination & Immunization for Women</h1>
      <p class="lead mb-4">
        Vaccines are an important part of preventive healthcare for women at all
        stages of life. Learn about recommended vaccinations, immunization
        schedules, and why they matter.
      </p>

      <div class="card mb-4">
        <div class="card-body">
          <h5 class="card-title">Important Vaccines for Women</h5>

          <div class="accordion" id="vaccineAccordion">
            <div class="accordion-item">
              <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingHPV">
                <button
                  class="accordion-button"
                  type="button"
                  data-bs-toggle="collapse"
                  data-bs-target="#collapseHPV"
                  aria-expanded="true"
                  aria-controls="collapseHPV"
                >
                  Human Papillomavirus (HPV) Vaccine
                </button>
              </h2>
              <div
                id="collapseHPV"
                class="accordion-collapse collapse show"
                aria-labelledby="headingHPV"
                data-bs-parent="#vaccineAccordion"
              >
                <div class="accordion-body">
                  <div class="row">
                    <div class="col-md-8">
                      <p>
                        <strong>Why it's important:</strong> HPV is the most
                        common sexually transmitted infection and can cause
                        cervical cancer and other cancers. The vaccine protects
                        against the types of HPV that most commonly cause these
                        cancers.
                      </p>
                      <p>
                        <strong>Recommended for:</strong> All people through age
                        26. For adults age 27 through 45, discuss with your
                        healthcare provider if vaccination might benefit you.
                      </p>
                      <p>
                        <strong>Schedule:</strong> Typically 2-3 doses,
                        depending on age at initial vaccination.
                      </p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="col-md-4">
                      <div class="text-center">
                        <i
                          class="fas fa-shield-virus fa-4x mb-3 text-primary"
                        ></i>
                      </div>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="accordion-item">
              <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingFlu">
                <button
                  class="accordion-button collapsed"
                  type="button"
                  data-bs-toggle="collapse"
                  data-bs-target="#collapseFlu"
                  aria-expanded="false"
                  aria-controls="collapseFlu"
                >
                  Influenza (Flu) Vaccine
                </button>
              </h2>
              <div
                id="collapseFlu"
                class="accordion-collapse collapse"
                aria-labelledby="headingFlu"
                data-bs-parent="#vaccineAccordion"
              >
                <div class="accordion-body">
                  <div class="row">
                    <div class="col-md-8">
                      <p>
                        <strong>Why it's important:</strong> Annual flu
                        vaccination reduces the risk of flu illness,
                        hospitalization, and death. It's especially important
                        for pregnant women, as it can help protect both mother
                        and baby.
                      </p>
                      <p>
                        <strong>Recommended for:</strong> Everyone 6 months and
                        older, annually.
                      </p>
                      <p>
                        <strong>Schedule:</strong> One dose every flu season
                        (typically fall/winter).
                      </p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="col-md-4">
                      <div class="text-center">
                        <i
                          class="fas fa-virus-slash fa-4x mb-3 text-primary"
                        ></i>
                      </div>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="accordion-item">
              <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingTdap">
                <button
                  class="accordion-button collapsed"
                  type="button"
                  data-bs-toggle="collapse"
                  data-bs-target="#collapseTdap"
                  aria-expanded="false"
                  aria-controls="collapseTdap"
                >
                  Tdap Vaccine (Tetanus, Diphtheria, Pertussis)
                </button>
              </h2>
              <div
                id="collapseTdap"
                class="accordion-collapse collapse"
                aria-labelledby="headingTdap"
                data-bs-parent="#vaccineAccordion"
              >
                <div class="accordion-body">
                  <div class="row">
                    <div class="col-md-8">
                      <p>
                        <strong>Why it's important:</strong> Protects against
                        tetanus, diphtheria, and pertussis (whooping cough).
                        Particularly important during pregnancy to protect
                        newborns from pertussis before they can be vaccinated.
                      </p>
                      <p>
                        <strong>Recommended for:</strong> All adults, with a
                        booster every 10 years. Pregnant women should receive
                        one dose during each pregnancy.
                      </p>
                      <p>
                        <strong>Schedule:</strong> One dose during each
                        pregnancy, preferably between 27 and 36 weeks.
                      </p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="col-md-4">
                      <div class="text-center">
                        <i class="fas fa-baby fa-4x mb-3 text-primary"></i>
                      </div>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="accordion-item">
              <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingHepB">
                <button
                  class="accordion-button collapsed"
                  type="button"
                  data-bs-toggle="collapse"
                  data-bs-target="#collapseHepB"
                  aria-expanded="false"
                  aria-controls="collapseHepB"
                >
                  Hepatitis B Vaccine
                </button>
              </h2>
              <div
                id="collapseHepB"
                class="accordion-collapse collapse"
                aria-labelledby="headingHepB"
                data-bs-parent="#vaccineAccordion"
              >
                <div class="accordion-body">
                  <div class="row">
                    <div class="col-md-8">
                      <p>
                        <strong>Why it's important:</strong> Hepatitis B is a
                        liver infection that can lead to serious health issues,
                        including liver cancer. The vaccine provides long-term
                        protection.
                      </p>
                      <p>
                        <strong>Recommended for:</strong> All infants at birth,
                        children and adults who were not vaccinated previously.
                      </p>
                      <p>
                        <strong>Schedule:</strong> Typically 3 doses over 6
                        months.
                      </p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="col-md-4">
                      <div class="text-center">
                        <i class="fas fa-liver fa-4x mb-3 text-primary"></i>
                      </div>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="accordion-item">
              <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingMMR">
                <button
                  class="accordion-button collapsed"
                  type="button"
                  data-bs-toggle="collapse"
                  data-bs-target="#collapseMMR"
                  aria-expanded="false"
                  aria-controls="collapseMMR"
                >
                  MMR Vaccine (Measles, Mumps, Rubella)
                </button>
              </h2>
              <div
                id="collapseMMR"
                class="accordion-collapse collapse"
                aria-labelledby="headingMMR"
                data-bs-parent="#vaccineAccordion"
              >
                <div class="accordion-body">
                  <div class="row">
                    <div class="col-md-8">
                      <p>
                        <strong>Why it's important:</strong> Protects against
                        measles, mumps, and rubella. Particularly important for
                        women of childbearing age, as rubella infection during
                        pregnancy can cause serious birth defects.
                      </p>
                      <p>
                        <strong>Recommended for:</strong> Adults born after 1957
                        who have not been vaccinated or do not have documented
                        immunity.
                      </p>
                      <p>
                        <strong>Note:</strong> Women should avoid becoming
                        pregnant for at least one month after receiving the MMR
                        vaccine.
                      </p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="col-md-4">
                      <div class="text-center">
                        <i
                          class="fas fa-shield-alt fa-4x mb-3 text-primary"
                        ></i>
                      </div>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card mb-4">
        <div class="card-body">
          <h5 class="card-title">Vaccines During Pregnancy</h5>
          <p>
            Vaccination during pregnancy not only protects the mother but can
            also protect the baby from certain diseases after birth through the
            transfer of antibodies.
          </p>

          <div class="table-responsive">
            <table class="table">
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Vaccine</th>
                  <th>Recommendation</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td>Influenza (Flu)</td>
                  <td>Recommended during any trimester of each pregnancy</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Tdap (Whooping Cough)</td>
                  <td>
                    Recommended during each pregnancy, ideally between 27-36
                    weeks
                  </td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>COVID-19</td>
                  <td>
                    Recommended for pregnant women based on current public
                    health guidelines
                  </td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td class="text-danger">MMR</td>
                  <td class="text-danger">Not recommended during pregnancy</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td class="text-danger">Varicella (Chickenpox)</td>
                  <td class="text-danger">Not recommended during pregnancy</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>

          <div class="alert alert-info">
            <i class="fas fa-info-circle me-2"></i> Always consult with your
            healthcare provider about which vaccines are appropriate for you
            during pregnancy.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-body">
          <h5 class="card-title">Common Questions About Vaccines</h5>

          <div class="mb-3">
            <h6>
              <i class="fas fa-question-circle me-2 text-primary"></i> Are
              vaccines safe?
            </h6>
            <p>
              Vaccines are thoroughly tested for safety before being approved
              for use. The benefits of vaccination far outweigh the potential
              risks for most people. Serious side effects are rare.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="mb-3">
            <h6>
              <i class="fas fa-question-circle me-2 text-primary"></i> Can I get
              vaccinated if I'm breastfeeding?
            </h6>
            <p>
              Most vaccines are safe for breastfeeding mothers. In fact, some
              antibodies from vaccines may pass through breast milk, providing
              some protection to the baby.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="mb-3">
            <h6>
              <i class="fas fa-question-circle me-2 text-primary"></i> What if I
              missed a vaccine as a child?
            </h6>
            <p>
              Many vaccines can be given as "catch-up" vaccines for adults who
              missed them in childhood. Talk to your healthcare provider about
              what you might need.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div>
            <h6>
              <i class="fas fa-question-circle me-2 text-primary"></i> Do I need
              vaccines if I'm planning to travel?
            </h6>
            <p>
              Depending on your destination, you may need additional vaccines.
              Some countries require proof of certain vaccinations for entry.
              Consult with a travel medicine specialist or your healthcare
              provider at least 4-6 weeks before international travel.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

